column169: On April 3, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN3098 was damaged prior to arrival and released approximately 55-gallons of product to the trailer interior and further migrated to the asphalt. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Thin Line Environmental (TLE) to remediate the impacted site. Crews collected the damaged 55-gallon drum and placed it in a 95-gallon over-pack drum for disposal. TLE deployed soda ash to the impacted asphalt and trailer floor to neutralize the release. Crews utilized hand tools to collect all impacted soda ash from the asphalt and the trailer floor. All hydrogen peroxide and peroxyacetic acid impacted material was collected and containerized in one (1) 95-gallon drum and thirteen (13) 35-gallon drums and added to RLC waste stream for disposal.

SequenceEvent: QA was made aware that there was leaking hazmat on the ground. QA was told that the driver had the package on their truck from the previous day and that when he opened up his side door the package fell out of his truck and onto the ground. The package was put into a plastic lined bin. QA stopped the continued downhill movement of the liquid with absorbent pads. The liquid was tested and came up acidic. Neutralizer was put onto the spill until it came up as non-acidic. Loose particulate was then placed on the spill area to absorb the liquid. DescribePack: The cap was loose on one of the jugs. The cap fell off after the package fell out of the drivers truck. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Neutralizer was used to negate the acid in the liquid. Loose particulate was placed on the spill.

On April 4, 2024, one (1) 275-gallon tote of corrosive liquid was punctured by a forklift and released approximately 115-gallons of product to the trailer interior and pavement beneath. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted site. HCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the impacted roadway/trailer interior and swept them in with hand tools. HCE utilized an additional tote to complete a gravity feed from the impacted 275-gallon tote. All spent absorbents, absorbent pads and collected waste were collected and containerized into six (6) 55-gallon metal drums and PPE was containerized into a separate 55-gallon open top poly drum. All were labeled and set aside for terminal disposal.

column169: SequenceEvent: The box was unloaded off the trailer. Then the box was transported to the van that was to deliver the box. An hour later, the driver of the van saw the box was leaking white small granules. The driver called a manager who came over to the van with gloves, broom, dustpan and a red hazmat plastic container. The manager put the box inside the red hazmat plastic container and swept up any granules that came out of the box. He then gently put the granules inside the box. The box was then transported to the hazmat cage by the Ops Admin. DescribePack: The bottom of the plastic bucket had a dent on the corner. The dent was about 3" long.  The bottom of the plastic bucket has a crack going along the outside seem about 8 inches long. Upon inspection saw underneath this plastic bottom was another plastic bottom. This inside plastic bottom was cracked in several places. The cracks ranged from 7 inches to 3 inches. I could see the product had leaked out of these cracks and the very outside crack. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: The box was turned upside down and placed inside a red plastic hazmat container. The leakage of the product stopped since the cracks were on the bottom of the plastic bucket that was inside the box.

column169: SequenceEvent: Package came off of truck in Unload notably wet, was placed into lined tote immediately and moved to safe area. Unable to determine if this occurred when initially loaded to trailer or during transit to our station. Upon opening outer packaging found one of four 4L bottles of water (non-hazardous) had somehow broken during shipping causing water to release inside package and eventually seep out as well. DescribePack: There were corrugated moldings around each of the four bottles to help protect during shipping but evidently was not enough to keep one bottle from getting broken. When that happened water leaked out inside, compromising structural integrity of inner, outer packaging and causing the box/moldings to tear and distort due to weight of 3 non-broken bottles. Bottle was already broken coming off of trailer so no knowledge of what directly caused damage to occur. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: Water had already leaked out due to bottle being broken completely. Cleaned up all wet areas in trailer and unload to re-establish safe working environment. Thankfully as stated through this report, the box was labeled as a Hazmat but did not contain any hazardous contents. Not sure if it was a mix-up by shipper when assigning labels to packages or what cause was, but no hazardous contents were in package or leaked out.

column169: On April 3, 2024, one (1) 330-gallon tote of glycol ether was damaged and released approximately five (5) gallons of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from TPM Group (TPM) to remediate the impacted site. Crews transferred the remaining contents of the damaged tote into two (2) separate 275-gallon totes and label as "DO NOT DELIVER." TPM utilized hand tools and absorbents to remediate the impacted surfaces. All waste was collected and containerized into two (2) 55-gallon drums and staged onsite with the damaged tote for disposal.

On April 1, 2024, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN3901 was damaged in transit due to unknown causes and released approximately 55-gallons of product to the trailer floor, pallets, and concrete. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from EnvioServe (ES) to remediate the impacted site. Crews deployed additional granular absorbents to the impacted area and worked them in with hand tools. Cleaners and absorbent pads were utilized to remove any residual product. The impacted pallet was dismantled for disposal. The dismantled pallet, the damaged drum, all UN3901 impacted materials, and spent absorbents were collected and containerized into one (1) 85-gallon overpack drum and nine (9) 55-gallon drums for disposal by R+L.

The impacted rags, damaged pallet, impacted gravel rocks, PPE, and poly were placed into a separate 55-gallon metal drum. The waste was transported back to the XPO terminal in Phoenix, AZ for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics terminal NCH experienced a UN1824 Greasestrip Plus release from a box containing (4) 1-gallon poly jugs as well as a release of UN3264 Lime-A-Way from a box containing (4) 1-gallon poly jugs. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-gallons of each product, (4-gallons combined) released to a 4’ x 4’ area of the trailer floor due to a forklift puncture. Soda ash solution and oil dri were deployed to clean and neutralize the impacted area. All impacted absorbents, cardboard, PPE, and the two empty pails of UN3264 Lime-A-Way were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The two empty jugs, and two damaged jugs of UN1824 Greasestrip Plus were placed into a separate 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
